{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523441"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13898"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13898"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.11,0.67,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53618"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6517"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39077"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2794"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44402"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53618"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, dry cough, and progressive shortness of breath. She reports severe fatigue and muscle aches. Her medical history is unremarkable, and she does not take any regular medications. She works as a veterinary nurse and recently treated several sick parrots at her clinic. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a temperature of 39.2\u00b0C, pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and SpO2 94% on room air. Chest auscultation reveals fine crackles at both lung bases. A chest X-ray shows patchy bilateral infiltrates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in establishing the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sputum culture for typical bacterial pathogens","Nasopharyngeal swab for respiratory viruses","Serum Chlamydophila psittaci antibody testing","Bronchoscopy with bronchoalveolar lavage","Chest CT scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the clinical presentation of atypical pneumonia and the patient\u0027s occupational exposure to birds, psittacosis (ornithosis) is the most likely diagnosis. The most appropriate next step to establish the diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum Chlamydophila psittaci antibody testing\u003C/strong\u003E. Psittacosis is caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003EChlamydophila psittaci\u003C/em\u003E, which is commonly found in birds, particularly parrots, cockatiels, and budgerigars. The diagnosis is typically based on clinical presentation, exposure history, and serological testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum culture for typical bacterial pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be helpful in this case, as \u003Cem\u003EC. psittaci\u003C/em\u003E is an intracellular organism that does not grow on standard culture media. Moreover, the clinical presentation is more consistent with an atypical pneumonia rather than a typical bacterial pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enasopharyngeal swab for respiratory viruses\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as part of a differential diagnosis, but given the strong suspicion for psittacosis based on the exposure history, serological testing for \u003Cem\u003EC. psittaci\u003C/em\u003E would be more specific and appropriate as the next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with bronchoalveolar lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that is not typically required for the diagnosis of psittacosis. It may be considered if the diagnosis remains unclear after less invasive tests or if the patient\u0027s condition deteriorates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E might provide more detailed imaging of the lung infiltrates, but it would not specifically diagnose psittacosis and is not necessary at this stage given the clear chest X-ray findings and clinical suspicion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the diagnosis is confirmed, treatment with doxycycline (a tetracycline antibiotic) is typically initiated. It\u0027s important to note that while serological testing is the most appropriate next step, treatment should not be delayed if psittacosis is strongly suspected, as early antibiotic therapy can significantly improve outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Psittacosis is an atypical pneumonia caused by Chlamydophila psittaci, typically associated with exposure to birds.","Diagnosis of psittacosis is often based on clinical presentation, exposure history, and serological testing.","Tetracyclines, particularly doxycycline, are the preferred treatment for psittacosis."],"references":["Dembek ZF, Mothershead JL, Owens AN, Chekol T, Wu A. Psittacosis: An Underappreciated and Often Undiagnosed Disease. Pathogens. 2023 Sep 15;12(9):1165. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10536718/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13898"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39077"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T13:01:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T13:03:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6517"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53618"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description"